q04_other_fear: in the shelter, he barked and barked and flung drool across his snout, and panted and whined really hard, constantly. he was very worked up the entire time in the kennel/shelter. he was like that when first arriving home, though not quite to that degree because it's quieter here and he got to get out, rather than being stuck behind bars. but i drugged him at night so we could all sleep. he gets anxious walking past other dogs still, but is not longer barking and lunging at them, but rather now knows to make eye contact with me. he's good in the car. i got to the end of this and you don't ask how he is now. he's a normal dog now, with me. he gets wound up with new people, but can calm down and lie quietly while they are here. he barks at the doorbell. he barks when people pass by the window. he lives with 3 other dogs and a cat (one dog and the cat have since died), which other "experts" have said could never happen. i worked with him at the shelter for about 2-3 months (?) before getting him out of there and then brought him home where he could become sane and not be treated with punishment, but rather de-stress and learn how to calm and be normal. he can still get snippy occasionally when one of my dogs gets too close (when something else exciting is going on, like strangers walking past the window and they're both barking), because the roomba bumped them together once, but for the most part he is a normal, sweet, loving, smart little guy. he loved the cat! i was told by an "expert" he could never be near a cat. in the 2 years since i've met him i have become a certified trainer in my own right, and the positive consistent methods have worked wonders with him. he was going to be put down by the shelter but by then he and i had become close, so i couldn't let that happen.

behavior_other_best: Different combinations work for different behaviours.For separation anxiety, structured desensitisation at the dog's pace worked best, alongside pheromone diffuser and a relaxation protocol before and after training sessions. Management is key to never leave alone beyond the duration that Beanie could cope.For fear of vets and husbandry, counterconditioning/desensitisation in increasing stress environments (home, vet waiting room and finally consultation room) works best. Although this is still in progress for us - Beanie has had a few bad visits due to a tumour and this has heightened his fear of strangers and vets even further.For social cues - like storming towards other dogs off lead - management like on-lead and reinforcing an incompatible behaviour works best.For all issues, an understanding of thresholds, triggers and body language is fundamental. Otherwise all the training is chaotic.

behavior_tech_other: Clementine's major behavorial issue when we adopted her (a little over 1 year ago) was voiding in the house. We understood that having spent her entire life in a kennel from the time of her rescue from a hoarding case at 8 weeks to when we adopted her at the age of two, just being in a house was going to be stressful for her. Unfortunately in her case, clicker training was not really an option, both because the sound was stressful and because she was so shut down from the stress that our only goal in the first year was acclimating the two of them to living closely with people in a home environment.When Clem did not want to go outside to use the bathroom, the only way to get her to go out was to carry her to the yard. Our schedule was very different from the rescue's schedule, of course, so establishing a new one was possibly confusing for them. Later on after she mastered going outside, Clemmie's sister, Pippi, would also 'assist' in getting Clemmie out.  We adopted both of them together. They are genetic siblings and the same age. Pippi did this by sniffing Clem's urethra, offering play signals and running out the back door, and even walking behind Clementine and trying to 'nudge' her from a sitting position into a standing position. Our house is configured so that Pippi and Clem have to pass through three doorways in two rooms to get into our large, fenced-in yard. (The size of the yard is probably a little bit stressful for these two, and so is the street noise. They like to go out in the dead of night and run around.) Passing through the gate, dutch door, or backdoor are part of the ritual of going outside now, too. Both of them get loads of verbal praise, touch, and a treat when they go outside. (They've both progressed to a point where they constantly and actively solicit physical contact. Clem is especially cuddly.)While Clem does have the patellar luxation, cauda equina syndrome, and hip dysplasia, she loves taking walks in a nearby National Park and her condition is well managed. The relative discomfort she feels from the patellar issue might cause her to delay going outside, but we don't believe it was the entire reason she was reluctant in the beginning of our relationship together. Clem is on a protocol of Adequan injections - which we administer once monthly at home - until our Vet tells us it's time for her first surgery. Clementine and Pippi both eat a high quality diet (Earthborn Holistic grain free fish formula) that helps manage skin conditions and Clementine's musculo-skeletal issues. They also get Omegas and Osteo True Benefits (both from Veterinary Recommended Solutions) in their food. They seem less mentally sluggish than they did when we adopted them - their diets could play a role. They look to us to figure out situations, they respond to our conversation, and they're tuned in.

behavior_tech_other: leadership protocol: not on owner's bed, follow owner through narrow spaces, move out of owner's way, owner initiates interactions, owner greets visitors before dog, dog walks behind owner in stressful situations. I used a prong collar to train the last behavior. I used perhaps a dozen jerks to establish the behavior in the first week. After a month we returned to a martingale collar (to prevent him slipping out of the collar since he has a small head), walking behind was by then on cue and we were and are able to walk pass dogs and cats he  would previously have reacted to. I observe that he sometimes will voluntarily move behind me. When he does that I frequently see a dog I hadn't noticed
behavior_other_best: The above includes many of the techniques I tried and we made small improvements with all of them, but the leadership protocol has been the only one that has resulted in our achieving the behavior I wanted: being able to calmly walk past dogs and cats.

behavior_tech_other: I occasionally use negative punishment followed by a directive or positive reinforcement for more serious issues (not basic obedience like sit, stay (as asked on the first page)) but barking too much and ignoring a command, biting (almost never a problem), not listening (after ample chances). The other method is time out (being put in a room, or area away from us, for a few minutes to show a behavior was unacceptable).
behavior_other_best: If he *is* going to have an issue with something (he has very few issues in general - usually something like barking excessively at dogs walking by, or begging too much), what works best is a combo of positive reinforcement and negative reinforcement, and communication. (I know neg. is largely not accepted. I'm careful to balance it, make sure it's having the desired effect, and never train out of anger, but feign it if need be.) He really does do best with a mix of the two. :) For specific issues (where punishment would be confusing, and positive reinforcing), time out works best. For training to walk nicely on the leash, it's all about communication and finding a happy medium. :) A retractable leash was a lifesaver there - he knows exactly how long it goes, not to pull, but he's free to explore, unless I do a recall or wait and ask him to sit for a passing car. We're still working on him letting my family play with my hair, or jokingly poke me, etc. without him worrying... this is pretty much his only unsolved issue (prob bc we have the least amount of chances to work on it).

best_prof_combo: This is hard because I have attended so many group classes, had individual consultations, attended Camp Gone to the Dogs 1-2 times per year,  in addition to attending conferences by John Rogerson, Sue Sternberg, Kay Laurence, Grisha Stewart, Suzanne Clothier, and others. What helped most of all was learning about dogs in general and dog behavior in order to understand them better. I attended Camp Gone to the dogs where Sue Sternberg would teach classes and give lectures and attended several of her workshops. What I learned from her about dog behavior and managing dog aggression was invaluable. A group class I took with my dog on impulse control was very helpful as well. The only person that was a credentialed dog trainer was Leslie Burgard in regards to individual consultations. But the thing that helped me most of all was learning everything I could about dogs and how they tick.

The final dog trainer I hired was the best and suggested we get my vet involved as well. To rule out health problems and to try Zylkene in addition to a wellness & training plan for Kawliga. After reading books & doing research to check my gut feelings about the misinformation I was being fed by, Cesar Milan DVD's, a random "dog behaviorist" & Bark Busters, I was lucky to find such amazing professionals to help me! Canine Training Behavior Specialists, LLC...out of Wilton CT.

behavior_tech_other: Nothing in life is free training, study of triggers I.e. what elicits a response from dog, journaling of behavior for better understanding, food rewards, safe places I.e. places for dog to go when fearful or uncomfortable I.e. specific corners or spots in room or sit on cough, timeouts i.e. put dog in quiet bedroom if something he might react to is going to happen I.e. put dog in bedroom if someone is carrying boxes into house so he doesn't have the oppurnity to react to the person carrying boxes, scheduling I.e. things happen at the same time mostly during the day I.e. breakfast, dinner, bed time etc...physical redirection I.e. prevent him from physical reacting to something I.e. going in opposite direction while on leash, standing in front of him while he sits and observes, using my body to direct him in the right direction I.e. moving him to safe spots by walking behind him or pointing, reinforcement of sit, if I ask or with hand signal to sit or whether he automatically does it in his spots, with food and praise all day everyday

best_prof_combo: The behavioralist I felt was a waste of our time. She essentially told us Steve will always have problems and to consider our decisions. 1) Adjust our way of life to accomodate his fear anxiety or 2) euthanasia.  Further talking with our own veterinarian, he made us feel more comfortable explaining Steve's fear anxiety was not caused by how we raised him but rather could have been a combination of genetics or the environment from which he came. The vet explained if his (steve's) mother had high anxiety during pregnancy or not good living situation, that stress could affect the litter.  Steve was prescribed prozac 40 mg to take daily. Although it makes him "sleepy", we don't see much improvement with his fear anxiety.  We keep him behind a gate when people visit with music and he usually will go to his crate which has become his safe haven.

desc_other_equip: I use voice and voice pitch with good results as I feel it is a communication style the dog recognizes within its canine family unit. A low pitched, stacatto  "leave it" and a high pitched "good boy" etc. I also use "tsk" verbal "clicking" to signal disapproval of an action but obviously I'm not a trainer, these have just worked well for me and I can get a dog to understand what I want very quickly.
behavior_other_best: Generally I spend a fair amount of time observing a dog so I can try to understand what his/her issues are before I try to train away bad behavior or promote new/good etc. In the context of the prison setting it was vital that new incoming dogs were assessed very quickly before assigning them to an inmate handler. I'm embarrassed to say that I don't recall which issue I wrote about in the first survey as it related to Connor - there have been quite a few. Connor has severe sensitivity to many foods and his allergies were undoubtedly making him uncomfortable. He is also very fearful of any items leaning against a wall or on the floor space he usually travels and he quickly develops triggers associated with past "traumas" e.g. he won't go down stairs he has used for years because recently a broom fell across the stairs as he was beginning to descend. Because Connor is somewhat of a fearful dog he is keen on deferring to me in most situations which cause him stress and we move quickly through situations which used to be problematic. For my part I've gotten better at learning what will cause him stress and I use habituation with lots of praise and lovely, smelly, treats to encourage him to push through. During play with other dogs he can be too enthusiastic and sometimes even a bit of a bully but will stand down quickly with a short "stop it". He's living with two canine siblings which has helped his reading of social cues a great deal -  albeit with a little help from me early on.

q05_other_rep: Slipper and sock stealing, a fetish for paper products such as paper towel and Kleenex, and one unusual pattern: When I give Pippin and Emma bones, he gets obsessed with wanting to get Emma's bone to see if she got the better deal. He always abandons his bone and "sucks up" to me in an effort to make Emma jealous and abandon her bone (she initially fell for this ploy but she quickly wised up). Emma has since learned to steal Pippin's abandoned bone and stack them all under the coffee table where she will guard them indefinitely from him until I relieve her of her burden and take them away (no aggression towards me). Pippin usually waits for her to get bored of her bone and eventually steals it and finishes off both her remaining bone (not really a bone, more of a chewy raw hide) and his own. There's always drama with poodles. LOL!I also wanted to note that Pippin's house soiling problem was limited to when he was a puppy, up to 10 months of age. Now he is relentless about being let outside when he has to go. Oh, that's another compulsive behaviour - always nagging us to let them out in the yard. Another repetitive behaviour: He has a specific place in the backyard where he barks. Normally while his sister Emma runs around like a crazed lunatic, Pippin sits back with his toy, quietly wagging his tail. He only goes to that certain spot to bark when he's in a particularly good mood. Another repetitive behaviour: Pippin enjoys knocking ALL of the pillows off the couch on a regular basis. He has this routine where he starts with he smaller pillows and moves his way up to the larger ones.  Another repetitive behaviour that happens many times a day (I have observed this countless times): When my husband goes into the basement to use the washroom, both Pippin and Emma stand frozen in front of their kennel. As soon as the toilet flushes, Pippin opens the kennel door with his paw and both dogs enter as my husband comes up the stairs. They stick their noses out the kennel door awaiting a treat. When we crate trained them as puppies during toilet training, they learned that if they went into their kennel/crate they got a treat. We no longer use the crate (as they can be trusted in the house now that they are adults) but they have "trained" my husband to give them treats in this particular situation.Another repetitive behaviour: When we let Pippin outside into the backyard, he always has to take a toy outside with him and he always has to bring a toy in (and it's not always th me same toy). He always jumps off the top stair onto the lower deck and he always waits to pee until our female pees (and he ALWAYS urinates on the spot where our female urinated).I wish I could go back and fill in Emma's survey again, there are other repetitive behaviours that she does that are popping into my mind now.

behavior_tech_other: Alpha rolls. This was the turning point several months after adopting him 13 yrs ago. That and the choke chain were making things worse, so I found "Culture Clash" and "Don't Shoot the Dog" as well as a beginner book on clicker training.I threw away the choke, put him in a plain harness to stop muscle memory, and we started clicker training. I had a lot of experience desensitizing 1 year old horses calmly and gently to new things, so drew on that experience of gradual desensitizing vs. using flooding in dogs as I had been taught by dog trainers.I completely crossed over, "Click to Calm" was my introduction to counter conditioning in dogs, even though I had been taught the the quadrants and read Skinner papers during my B.S. in Animal Sciences.He did very well when I started shaping how he approached dogs off lead with the clicker. He was able to learn to approach in an arch vs. head on, and had an excellent recall. He was never in a fight, but was initially posturing with unknown n/m.I also determined that known play groups were a better choice vs an actual dog park after learning stress signals in case study books.
behavior_other_best: Read above the cross over to force free, clicker based training. I did not use a NRM with him as it was frustrating to him and did not use extinction as I redirected and asked for a known behavior.

q05_other_rep: Djinn has done the spinning/ tail chasing thing since I got him at 8 weeks.  I put it on cue, because it was cute, and now he really only does it when cued. I compete with Djinn in frisbee, and he would chase his tail if we had to wait too long on the field before being allowed to start our routine.  As he grows and gains confidence, I see less and less of this behavior.  His other repetitive behavior is destroying frisbees.  He chews them into tiny pieces, and he really loves doing it, so I use disc-destruction as a reward for not chewing the discs on the field.  It started as an unwanted behavior that was complicating his disc training, now I use it as a reward.  It's working, he is the current Colorado State Champ.
